Switching users: s-u versus sudo.

There are two ways to run a command as a different user, and the difference between them matters a great deal. The first is s-u, short for substitute user. It starts a new shell as another user, and crucially it prompts for that other user's password. On its own it makes you root; given a username it makes you that user. The most important detail is the dash flag. Without it, you become the other user but keep your own environment, your current directory and variables. With it, you simulate a fresh login: it runs their login scripts and drops you into their home directory.

The second is sudo, short for substitute user do. It runs a single command as another user, root by default, and it prompts for your own password rather than the target's. It can run an interactive root shell, run a command as a specific other user, or forget its cached credentials so the next use prompts again.

Sudo is the modern, recommended approach for almost everything, and the comparison shows why. S-u asks for the target's password, which means everyone who needs root must share the root password; sudo asks for your own, so the root password can be locked away entirely. Sudo logs every command for auditing; s-u does not. Sudo allows a fine-grained allow-list of exactly which commands each person may run; s-u is all or nothing. And sudo's authority is time-limited, cached for only a few minutes. On ubuntu and most cloud images the root account is locked with no password at all, and every administrative action goes through sudo. That is the right pattern: a single shared root account is hard to audit, whereas per-user sudo policies are easy.
